        {
            "id": "intro_else_finally",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Else and Finally",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Beyond `try` and `except`, Python has two more useful blocks: `else` and `finally`. They give you even more control over error handling."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "These blocks help you organize code that runs in different situations."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "else_block",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The Else Block",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `else` block runs **only if no error occurred** in the try block. It's perfect for code that should only run on success."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "try:\n    number = int(\"25\")\nexcept ValueError:\n    print(\"Invalid input\")\nelse:\n    print(f\"Converted: {number}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Converted: 25"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `else` block runs because no error occurred. If there had been an error, only the `except` block would run."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "else_vs_try",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Why use else instead of putting code in try?** It makes it clear which code might cause errors and which is the success case."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "try:\n    result = 10 / 2\nexcept ZeroDivisionError:\n    print(\"Cannot divide by zero\")\nelse:\n    print(f\"Result: {result}\")\n    print(\"Division successful!\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Result: 5.0\nDivision successful!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `else` block contains code that should run after successful division."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
